@node object010008D8 "NGC 2264, Cone Nebula, Christmas Tree Cluster"
@{"View Picture" system "execute DUDemo:showpic deepsky/ngc2264.jpeg"}

@remark beginverbatim
 Discoverer...................unknown
 Distance.....................2,600 light years
 True diameter................20 light years
 Number of stars..............hundreds
@remark endverbatim

NGC 2264 is a loose @{"open cluster" link define.guide/opencluster}, surrounded by @{"nebulosity" link define.guide/nebula}. Its shape is
reminiscent of a christmas tree, hence the name.

The 20 brightest stars range from @{"magnitude" link define.guide/magnitude} 4.6 to 9.3, and their
@{"spectral types" link define.guide/spectralclassification} vary between O and K (a substantial range).  Radio emissions
have been detected from the cluster and surrounding nebula.

NGC 2264 is one of the youngest star clusters known (2 million years old), and
the area is likely still a region of active star formation.

There are two primary nebulae associated with the cluster.  A dark nebula (the
Cone Nebula) is silhouetted against a much brighter background
@{"reflection nebula" link define.guide/reflectionnebula}.
@endnode

