@node object0000080D "Betelgeuse"
Betelgeuse (pronounced BAY-tel-jooz) is a bright red giant star in the
@{"constellation" link define.guide/constellation} of Orion.  Its name is believed to have come from the Arabic
`Beit Algueze', meaning the "Armpit of the Giant".

This star is an @{"irregular variable" link define.guide/irregularvariable}, with a period roughly 5.7 years long.  The
star has been measured at @{"magnitudes" link define.guide/magnitude} between 0.4 and 1.2 in recent history, but
the brightness variations are quite irregular.  Spectroscopic studies show that
during periods of maximum brightness, the diameter of the star may actually
increase to a size 60% larger than its size when faint.  The star is so large
that if it were to replace our Sun, it will engulf Mercury, Venus, Earth, and
Mars.  During periods of its maximum size, Jupiter would be in jeopardy as
well.

Betelgeuse is believed to be located about 520 light years away.  To shine as
brightly in our skies as it does, astronomers infer that it must be 10,000
times more powerful than our Sun.
@endnode

